Vaulted Rotunda~
   This atrium's most distinguishing characteristic is its high vaulted
ceilings with numerous pointed arches that reach upward from elaborate stone
pillars lining the semicircular walls.  Apparently constructed of sturdy
limestone, the ceiling puts tremendous weight on its supporting posts,
indicated by the great lines of blue steel reinforcing the walls.  The
beautiful stone walls wrap around in an arc that opens up to a huge arch
leading to the sanctuary to the west.  In the east, a smaller arch leads to the
cathedral antechamber, above which a beautiful, tall stained glass window is
emplaced.  Unlike typical stained glass windows, this one has primarily muted
colors, many of which are blues and grays.  Similar but smaller stained glass
windows appear periodically around the upper circumference of the rotunda walls
where they meet the vaulted ceiling.  To the north and south, smaller arched
doorways open to twin narthexes.  Barely noticeable in the center of the
checkered marble floor is the vague shape of a fox, made up of a slightly
darker, bluish marble.    
